		<div class="title">
			
			<h4><a id="comment_link_71969" name="comment_link_71969" href="//use.perl.org/comments.pl?sid=44783&amp;cid=71969" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(71969)">Oh, and it becomes thread-safer</a>
			
			<span id="comment_score_71969" class="score">(<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 71969); return false">Score:1</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			by
			<a href="//use.perl.org/~masak/">masak (6289)</a>
			
			
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_71969"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_71969"><p>Either I didn't think of it at the time of blogging, or I forgot about it, but another nice thing about using contextuals rather than instance attributes is that the class becomes thread-safe. In other words, you can suddenly use the same instance of Yapsi::Compiler to compile two different sources simultaneously. The contextuals will be local to each thread and not interact; instance attributes would have been shared and cause a bit of trouble.</p><p>Yapsi::Compiler currently only has one instance attribute: @.wa<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
		
	
	</div>
	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_71969"></div>

